<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-031-236 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 526 153</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Oct 21 1991 v8 n42 p47(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Evaluating LAN security. (local area network)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Patterson, Thomas.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Security systems for local area networks (LANs) require thoroughpreparation, constant monitoring and a significant timecommitment, but ultimately the security system may avoid downtime,file damage and legal hassles.andP;  The implementation of a LANimmediately becomes susceptible to natural disaster, hackerinvasion, employee tampering, user mistakes, viruses andindustrial espionage.andP;  These vulnerabilities can be avoided orfixed with the incorporation of file encryption, disaster recoveryplans, audit trails, access controls and virus protectionsoftware.andP;  Network managers should make sure that there aresecurity management interfaces that can simply describe securityconfigurations to users and that any new operating systems addedto a system are compatible with the complete security systeminstalled.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Local area networksData SecurityData ManagementAccess ControlsEncryptionAudit TrailsNetwork Management.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>